{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568320"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:13:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:13:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20035"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20035","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20035"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.51,0.1,0.13,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12814"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109126"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12814"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20035"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91485"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"45"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5799"},{"type":"tags","id":"5820"},{"type":"tags","id":"5977"},{"type":"tags","id":"6281"},{"type":"tags","id":"8831"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11641"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"30248"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35336"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35543"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40738"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43731"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44888"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109126"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department following a rear-end motor vehicle collision two hours ago. She reports neck pain and stiffness that developed shortly after the accident. She has no neurological symptoms, no headache, and no loss of consciousness. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She has tenderness over her cervical paraspinal muscles with reduced range of movement in all directions. Neurological examination is normal with intact sensation, power, and reflexes in all limbs. A computed tomography scan of her cervical spine shows no fracture or acute pathology. A hyperextension-flexion neck injury is suspected.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is required as part of the diagnostic process in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Positive magnetic resonance imaging findings","Exclusion of cervical spine fracture","Symptoms persisting for at least 48 hours","Evidence of ligamentous injury on imaging","Presence of neurological symptoms"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHyperextension-flexion neck injuries (commonly known as whiplash) are clinical diagnoses based on the mechanism of injury and presenting symptoms, rather than specific imaging findings. The diagnosis is made when there is neck pain following a hyperextension-flexion injury, typically from a rear-end motor vehicle collision.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExclusion of cervical spine fracture\u003C/strong\u003E is required before diagnosing a hyperextension-flexion injury. While these injuries themselves are clinical diagnoses, it is essential to exclude more serious injuries such as fractures or spinal cord injury before establishing this diagnosis. This is typically done with plain radiographs or computed tomography in the acute setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositive magnetic resonance imaging findings\u003C/strong\u003E are not required for the diagnosis of hyperextension-flexion injuries. MRI may show soft tissue injuries in some cases, but these findings correlate poorly with symptoms and prognosis. Many patients with clinical hyperextension-flexion injuries have normal MRI findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESymptoms persisting for at least 48 hours\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Symptoms typically develop within 24 hours of injury, and there is no minimum duration required for diagnosis. In fact, early recognition allows for appropriate management to begin promptly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEvidence of ligamentous injury on imaging\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While ligamentous injuries may occur in hyperextension-flexion injuries, they are not always present or detectable on imaging. The diagnosis is based on clinical findings rather than specific structural abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPresence of neurological symptoms\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary for diagnosis. Most patients with hyperextension-flexion injuries do not have neurological deficits. When neurological symptoms are present, they may indicate a more severe injury requiring different management approaches.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key elements in diagnosing hyperextension-flexion injuries include: appropriate mechanism of injury (typically acceleration-deceleration forces), development of neck pain and stiffness following the injury, exclusion of fractures or other serious pathology, and absence of pre-existing conditions that would better explain the symptoms. Management typically includes reassurance, appropriate analgesia, and early mobilisation rather than prolonged immobilisation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hyperextension-flexion neck injuries from motor vehicle collisions commonly present with neck pain and reduced range of motion without neurological deficits.","Imaging in neck trauma is primarily used to exclude serious injuries like fractures rather than to diagnose soft tissue injuries.","Early mobilisation and appropriate analgesia are key components in the management of acute neck injuries following motor vehicle collisions."],"references":["Li F, Liu N, Li H, Zhang B, Tian S, Tan M, Sandoz, B. A review of neck injury and protection in vehicle accidents. Transp Saf Environ. 2019 Nov 1;1(2):89\u2013105. https://doi.org/10.1093/tse/tdz012","Alao T, Waseem M. Neck Trauma. [Updated 2023 Jul 3]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470422/","Strudwick K, McPhee M, Bell A, Martin-Khan M, Russell T. Review article: Best practice management of neck pain in the emergency department (part 6 of the musculoskeletal injuries rapid review series). Emerg Med Australas. 2018 Dec;30(6):754-772. doi: 10.1111/1742-6723.13131. Epub 2018 Aug 30. PMID: 30168261. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30168261/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91485"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20035"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91485","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91485"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-17T20:28:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-17T20:29:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12814"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109126"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","nam